 bene\nfit of the people,\ni The second guide to business\naction has to do with Inven\ntoriee.\nWe have reports of some\nmanufacturers and distributors\nwho are going along on a hand\nto-mouth Inventory basis.\nRales Leas Noted\nOne businessman told me re\ncently that this kind of timidity\nhad been bad business for him.\nHe was convinced that It had\ncaused him to lose \u2014les. An\nother told me that his com\npany's policy, back In IMB, of\nletting In van tori\u2014 fall below'\nnormal requirements left It un\nable to keep up with Its com\npetitors when the upswing\ncame.\nThe guide In this Inventory\nquestion seems a common\nsen\u2014 one: Buy to normal re\nquirement* Is that good busi\nness?\nClosely related is a third\nproblem, that of Investment In\nplant and equipment.\nNow, no one is going to urge\na buelne\u2014 with ample capacity\nto add more facilities just be\ncause it might be good for the\neconomy as a whole.\nOn the other hand, very few\nof the 4.3 million Individual\nbusiness\u2014 in this country feel\nthat they do not need some\nmodernization or Improvement.\nPint they expect to create bet\nter values for oetter business\ntoday. Likewise, they want to\nget ready to win their full share\nof the unprecedented markets\nthat certainly He ahead. Many\nof the\u2014 companies are doing\nthese things now. for the sim\niple reason that now Is a good\n'time to get them done\nWhat time coulo be better\nthan the present for making\n'the\u2014 outlays? Money andli\nmaterlsls an mors readily 1\navailable today, and In many\ncaa\u2014 on better terms, than f\nthey have been for some time\u2014 I\nor than they may be for tome\ntime. t\nAa I have Indicated, the uov- f\neminent Is following this sim\nple rule: Por purchases and in- I\nvestments which must be made\nanyway, acting now makes\nten\u2014 for the Government. And I\nIt glv\u2014 the economy a lift when I\nif* most helpful. I sugg-t that I\nthere an numerous opportune\nties for private business profit\nably to adapt the same prlncl-\npie to its operations. I\n\nPrice Comment 1\nMy fourth comment Is on\nprlc\u2014. 1\nNo feature of America's eco-\nnomlc life h\u2014 been more at\nthe heart of our rapidly rising i\nand widely shared levels of I\nliving than the daring of this\nNation's business\u2014 In pricing\nfor volume and taking their\nchances on profits. It Is no\naccident that this policy has\ncharacterized our most profit-\nable lndustrl\u2014. If we are to\nmaintain the vigor and vitality\njof our free economy, this drive\nI for the widest possible markets\nmust continue. A price policy\ndesigned to bring Increasing\nvolume should be nothing short\nof an article of faith for every j\nbusinessman.\nMy fifth observation is this:\nthe economic recovery and\n;growth we bring about must;\ntake the form, not of higher\ncosts and prlc\u2014. but of more\nproduction and more jobs.\nLet's be realistic. If as earn\ners we obtain such large in\ncreases In our Incomes each\nyear that the costs of produc\ntion move always upward, then\nas customers we will find only\nhigher price tags in the stores.\ntrie* Restraint\nThe American people be- 1\nlieve In good wages, both In:\nprivate and public employment.\nGood wages reward effort and\nbuild markets. But the Amer\nican people are going to be\nlooking over the shoulders of\nthose sitting at every bargain\ning table to see whether the\nI wage settlement and subse\nquent price decisions are con\nsistent with a stable dollar,\nor whether they mean another\ndismal sequence of ever-rising\ncosts and prices.\nInequities in the wage struc\nture must, of course, be ad\njusted. But consumers are not\ngoing to be satisfied with less\nand less value per dollar of\nprice, which Is the inevitable\nresult of less and less produc\ntion per dollar of cost. If busi\nnessmen and labor union lead\ners forget these truths, the con\nsumer will remind them In ways\ni that are clear and painful. And\nin the process the whole econ\n!omy will suffer. These are not\ntheoretical considerations. They\nhave a direct bearing on specific\nIndustries today.\nIdeas for Oblivion\nPerhaps this is a good time to\nask ourselves whether some\ni dangerous rigidities of thought\nand polley have not b\u2014n settl-r\nina In on us In reeent years. I\nThar* used to be a periodical i\nfeature entitled, \u201cWe nominate\nfor oblivion. I\nLet me suggest a few lde\u2014 i\nthat I would like to nominate i\nfor oblivion:\n\u2014The id\u2014 that the consumer\nis not price conscious any,\nmore:\n\u2014The notion that without;\npaying the piper In higher'\nprlc\u2014, we can as a Nation over\npay ourselves for what we pro- i\nduce:\n\u2014The Id\u2014 that management\ncan be las about costa without\npricing its product, not only out\nof foreign markets, but out of\nthe American market as well;\n\u2014The Idea that large annual\nwage Increases can be regarded\nas a matter of course;\n\u2014The delusion that more\nrigid farm controls and larger\nsurpluses to dispose of at tax\npayer expense can lead to a 1\nprosperous farm economy;\n\u2014The notion that we can\nexport without Importing;\n\u2014The doctrine that a com\npetitive enterprise economy can\nbe free of all loss, failure and\ndisappointment, and that Gov\nernment can take all the bumps\nout of the road of business.\nAll these and similar Ulu-j\nsions are threats to that\nresiliency which enables private\nenterprise to adjust Itself to\nnew conditions. More than\nthat, they are threats to\nrecovery and to our capacity to;\nachieve a vigorous and orderly\neconomic growth. I once more\nnominate the whole kit and ka\nboodle of them for oblivion.\nFaith Justified\nThree jc\u2014rs ago last October.\nI discussed the state of the\n1 economy in an address at the\nForrestal Memorial Dinner In\nADVERTISEMENT\nCool Comfort\nFor Burning Feet\nUt Ics-Mlat with soothing lanolin kMp\nEfott In cool, trash comfort while the\nnratura soars. So auy to apply this\ny-white medicated cream \u2014s